                                                "fillArea": false,
                                                "textSize": 1,
                                                "textBackground": "none",
                                                "placeholderInvisible": false,
                                                "placeholderStretch": true,
                                                "placeholderHeight": 50,
                                                "useFigureAdditionalScale": false,
                                                "figureAdditionalScale": 1,
                                                "imgHeight": 300,
                                                "imgFit": "inside",
                                                "imgStretch": true,
                                                "hideFigureCaption": false,
                                                "hideFigureSubCaption": false,
                                                "hideFigureFootnote": false,
                                                "markdown": "Zambia has made important commitments to improving maternal, newborn, child, and adolescent health through national strategies aligned to universal health coverage and primary health care strengthening. Antenatal care is a cornerstone of these efforts, providing an entry point for prevention, early detection of complications, and linkage to skilled delivery. At the same time, the health sector is operating in a constrained fiscal environment, requiring greater emphasis on value for money and results-based service delivery. Within this context, optimizing existing platforms\u2014particularly immunization and maternal health services\u2014offers a timely opportunity to improve outcomes for women and children by leveraging current system capacity, strengthening continuity of care, and ensuring that limited resources are directed toward the highest-impact interventions.\n\n"
                                            }
                                        }
                                    ]
                                },
                                {
                                    "type": "cols",
                                    "id": "89c9d140-cfa6-40d8-a892-f365155296f1",
                                    "children": [
                                        {
                                            "type": "item",
                                            "id": "6cdf3a11-5a07-42ff-9236-43886604fb2c",
                                            "data": {
                                                "type": "text",
                                                "stretch": true,
                                                "fillArea": false,
                                                "textSize": 1,
                                                "textBackground": "none",
                                                "placeholderInvisible": false,
                                                "placeholderStretch": true,
                                                "placeholderHeight": 50,
                                                "useFigureAdditionalScale": false,
                                                "figureAdditionalScale": 1,
                                                "imgHeight": 300,
                                                "imgFit": "inside",
                                                "imgStretch": true,
                                                "hideFigureCaption": false,
                                                "hideFigureSubCaption": false,
                                                "hideFigureFootnote": false,
                                                "markdown": "# Problem Statement                                   \nZambia\u2019s ANC4 challenge is not primarily a financing gap\u2014it is an efficiency, equity, and service completion gap. Significant provincial variation in coverage shows that strong performance is achievable within existing resources, yet too many women are lost between early ANC visits and ANC4 due to weak follow-up and uneven service delivery. Addressing this requires shifting from input maintenance to performance improvement: systematically learning from high-performing provinces, strengthening appointment tracking and community follow-up, and smoothing delivery across districts and months. Reinvesting the resulting efficiency gains will ensure that every woman who enters antenatal care completes her full care pathway, improving maternal and newborn outcomes while making better use of existing public resources.\n\n"
                                            }
                                        }
                                    ]
                                }
                            ]
                        },
